{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RFP9MwycwHEFdECw6LhrKb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You write a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, point Cloche at a project directory, and it\n     5→handles execution, retry logic, and status tracking.\n     6→\n     7→## Prerequisites\n     8→\n     9→- Go 1.25+\n    10→- Docker\n    11→- Git\n    12→- An `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (for agent steps using Claude Code)\n    13→\n    14→For detailed installation options (pre-built binaries, `go install`, Homebrew,\n    15→Docker-based usage), see [INSTALL.md](INSTALL.md).\n    16→\n    17→## Quick Start\n    18→\n    19→### 1. Build everything\n    20→\n    21→```\n    22→make build\n    23→make docker-build\n    24→```\n    25→\n    26→This produces `bin/cloche`, `bin/cloched`, `bin/cloche-agent`, and the\n    27→`cloche-agent:latest` Docker image.\n    28→\n    29→### 2. Start the daemon\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→bin/cloched\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→The daemon listens on a Unix socket at `/tmp/cloche.sock` by default. It\n    36→manages Docker containers, tracks run state in SQLite, and handles\n    37→container cleanup. Containers are automatically removed after successful\n    38→runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their\n    39→container for debugging.\n    40→\n    41→To enable the web dashboard, set `CLOCHE_HTTP` (e.g.\n    42→`CLOCHE_HTTP=:8080 bin/cloched`). The dashboard is not started unless\n    43→this variable is set.\n    44→\n    45→### 3. Run a workflow\n    46→\n    47→From your project directory (must be inside a git repository):\n    48→\n    49→```\n    50→cd my-project\n    51→cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add user authentication\"\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→This will:\n    55→1. Write your prompt to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`\n    56→2. Create a Docker container and copy your entire project into it (no bind mounts)\n    57→3. Apply any override files from `.cloche/overrides/` on top\n    58→4. Start the container, which runs `cloche-agent` to walk the workflow graph\n    59→5. When the workflow finishes, the daemon extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch\n    60→\n    61→### 4. Monitor progress\n    62→\n    63→```\n    64→cloche status <run-id>\n    65→cloche list\n    66→```\n    67→\n    68→### 5. Get the results\n    69→\n    70→When the run completes, the agent's work is on a git branch:\n    71→\n    72→```\n    73→git branch | grep cloche/\n    74→git diff main..cloche/<run-id>\n    75→```\n    76→\n    77→To merge results into your working branch:\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→git merge cloche/<run-id>\n    81→# or cherry-pick, rebase, etc.\n    82→```\n    83→\n    84→To clean up run branches:\n    85→\n    86→```\n    87→git branch -D cloche/<run-id>\n    88→```\n    89→\n    90→## Container Isolation Model\n    91→\n    92→Cloche provides **total filesystem isolation** between the host and container:\n    93→\n    94→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the entire project root into the container at\n    95→  `/workspace/`. No bind mounts for project files. Override files from\n    96→  `.cloche/overrides/` are then copied on top (e.g., a container-specific\n    97→  `CLAUDE.md`). The `.git/` directory is included so agents have git context.\n    98→- **Files out**: When the workflow completes, the daemon extracts results from\n    99→  the container via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits them to a\n   100→  `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   101→- **Auth mounts**: `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` are bind-mounted read-only\n   102→  for Claude Code OAuth session reuse. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed as an\n   103→  environment variable.\n   104→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   105→\n   106→Your project directory is never modified by the container. All changes live\n   107→on the run branch until you explicitly merge them.\n   108→\n   109→## CLI Reference\n   110→\n   111→### `cloche init`\n   112→\n   113→Scaffold a new Cloche project in the current directory.\n   114→\n   115→```\n   116→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   120→|------|---------|-------------|\n   121→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   122→| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   123→\n   124→Creates `.cloche/` with a workflow file, Dockerfile, configuration file\n   125→(`config.toml`), prompt templates (`implement.md`, `fix.md`,\n   126→`update-docs.md`), a host orchestration workflow (`host.cloche`), a\n   127→prompt generation script (`scripts/prepare-prompt.sh`), and a version\n   128→marker. Skips files that already exist.\n   129→Also adds gitignore entries for runtime state directories.\n   130→\n   131→### `cloche health`\n   132→\n   133→Show project health summary based on recent run results.\n   134→\n   135→```\n   136→cloche health\n   137→```\n   138→\n   139→Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` to be set (e.g. `export CLOCHE_HTTP=localhost:8080`).\n   140→Fetches health data from the daemon's HTTP API (`GET /api/projects`) and\n   141→displays a table with per-project pass/fail counts:\n   142→\n   143→```\n   144→PROJECT          STATUS    PASSED  FAILED  TOTAL\n   145→my-project       green     5       0       5\n   146→other-project    yellow    3       2       5\n   147→```\n   148→\n   149→Status is colored (green/yellow/red) when output is a TTY.\n   150→\n   151→### `cloche run`\n   152→\n   153→Launch a workflow run.\n   154→\n   155→```\n   156→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   157→```\n   158→\n   159→| Flag | Description |\n   160→|------|-------------|\n   161→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche` in the project directory. |\n   162→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` and injected into agent steps. |\n   163→| `--keep-container` | Keep the Docker container even on success (default: remove on success). Failed runs always keep their container for debugging. |\n   164→\n   165→The current working directory is used as the project directory. It must be\n   166→inside a git repository (Cloche needs the repo root for result extraction\n   167→via git worktrees).\n   168→\n   169→When starting a run, the daemon checks whether the Docker image is up-to-date\n   170→with the project's `.cloche/Dockerfile`. If the Dockerfile has changed since\n   171→the last build (tracked via a SHA-256 label on the image), the daemon rebuilds\n   172→the image automatically before launching the container.\n   173→\n   174→### `cloche status`\n   175→\n   176→Check the status of a run.\n   177→\n   178→```\n   179→cloche status <run-id>\n   180→```\n   181→\n   182→Output includes the run state, active steps, and per-step results with timestamps.\n   183→\n   184→### `cloche list`\n   185→\n   186→List runs (last hour by default).\n   187→\n   188→```\n   189→cloche list [--all]\n   190→```\n   191→\n   192→| Flag | Description |\n   193→|------|-------------|\n   194→| `--all` | Show all runs, not just the last hour. |\n   195→\n   196→Columns: run ID, workflow name, state, container ID (if running), error message (if failed).\n   197→\n   198→### `cloche logs`\n   199→\n   200→Show logs for a run.\n   201→\n   202→```\n   203→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [--follow]\n   204→```\n   205→\n   206→| Flag | Description |\n   207→|------|-------------|\n   208→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   209→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Show only logs of the specified type (`full` = unified log, `script` = script output, `llm` = LLM conversation). |\n   210→| `--follow`, `-f` | Stream live log lines via SSE. Color-coded by type: status (blue), LLM (green), script (default). Exits when the run completes. Connects to the daemon's HTTP endpoint (see `CLOCHE_HTTP` in Client Configuration). |\n   211→\n   212→Without flags, shows the unified log (`full.log`) if available, otherwise streams\n   213→step start/completion events and run results.\n   214→With `--follow`, connects to the SSE endpoint and prints log lines in real-time.\n   215→\n   216→### `cloche poll`\n   217→\n   218→Wait for a run to finish, printing progress updates.\n   219→\n   220→```\n   221→cloche poll <run-id>\n   222→```\n   223→\n   224→Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure or if the container\n   225→dies unexpectedly.\n   226→\n   227→### `cloche stop`\n   228→\n   229→Cancel a running workflow.\n   230→\n   231→```\n   232→cloche stop <run-id>\n   233→```\n   234→\n   235→### `cloche delete`\n   236→\n   237→Delete a retained Docker container. Accepts either a Docker container name/ID\n   238→or a Cloche run ID. If given a run ID, the daemon looks up the associated\n   239→container.\n   240→\n   241→```\n   242→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   243→```\n   244→\n   245→### `cloche orchestrate`\n   246→\n   247→Dispatch ready workflow runs for the current project. Checks the project's\n   248→issue tracker for unclaimed tasks, generates prompts, and launches runs.\n   249→\n   250→```\n   251→cloche orchestrate\n   252→```\n   253→\n   254→Uses the current working directory as the project directory. Prints \"No ready\n   255→work found.\" if there are no tasks to dispatch, or \"Dispatched N run(s).\"\n   256→with the count.\n   257→\n   258→### `cloche shutdown`\n   259→\n   260→Shut down the daemon.\n   261→\n   262→```\n   263→cloche shutdown\n   264→```\n   265→\n   266→## Setting Up a New Project\n   267→\n   268→### 1. Scaffold the project\n   269→\n   270→Run `cloche init` from your project root to create the `.cloche/` directory with\n   271→default workflow, Dockerfile, and prompt templates:\n   272→\n   273→```\n   274→cd my-project\n   275→cloche init\n   276→```\n   277→\n   278→Or create the structure manually:\n   279→\n   280→### 2. Create a workflow file\n   281→\n   282→Add `.cloche/<name>.cloche`:\n   283→\n   284→```\n   285→workflow \"develop\" {\n   286→  step implement {\n   287→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n   288→    results = [success, fail]\n   289→  }\n   290→\n   291→  step test {\n   292→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n   293→    results = [success, fail]\n   294→  }\n   295→\n   296→  step fix {\n   297→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   298→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   299→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   300→  }\n   301→\n   302→  step update-docs {\n   303→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/update-docs.md\")\n   304→    results = [success, fail]\n   305→  }\n   306→\n   307→  implement:success -> test\n   308→  implement:fail -> abort\n   309→\n   310→  test:success -> update-docs\n   311→  test:fail -> fix\n   312→\n   313→  fix:success -> test\n   314→  fix:fail -> abort\n   315→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   316→\n   317→  update-docs:success -> done\n   318→  update-docs:fail -> done\n   319→}\n   320→```\n   321→\n   322→### 3. Write prompt templates\n   323→\n   324→Create `.cloche/prompts/` with markdown files:\n   325→\n   326→**`.cloche/prompts/implement.md`** — Instructions for the initial implementation:\n   327→```markdown\n   328→You are working on a project. Implement the following change:\n   329→\n   330→## User Request\n   331→(The user prompt is injected automatically by the agent adapter)\n   332→\n   333→## Guidelines\n   334→- Follow existing project conventions\n   335→- Write tests for new functionality\n   336→- Run tests locally before declaring success\n   337→```\n   338→\n   339→**`.cloche/prompts/fix.md`** — Instructions for fixing failures:\n   340→```markdown\n   341→The previous attempt had failures. Review the output logs in .cloche/output/\n   342→and fix the issues.\n   343→\n   344→## Guidelines\n   345→- Read the test/lint output carefully\n   346→- Fix the root cause, not the symptoms\n   347→- Run tests again to verify your fix\n   348→```\n   349→\n   350→**`.cloche/prompts/update-docs.md`** — Instructions for keeping docs in sync:\n   351→```markdown\n   352→Review the CLI source code and update usage documentation to reflect any changes.\n   353→```\n   354→\n   355→### 4. Add overrides (optional)\n   356→\n   357→Files in `.cloche/overrides/` are copied on top of `/workspace/` in the\n   358→container. Use this for container-specific configuration:\n   359→\n   360→```\n   361→.cloche/overrides/\n   362→  CLAUDE.md              # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (replaces host version)\n   363→```\n   364→\n   365→### 5. Make sure your project builds in the container\n   366→\n   367→The default Dockerfile generated by `cloche init` uses `cloche-base:latest` as its\n   368→base image (configurable via `--base-image`). If your project needs different\n   369→dependencies, edit `.cloche/Dockerfile`:\n   370→\n   371→```dockerfile\n   372→FROM golang:1.25 AS builder\n   373→WORKDIR /src\n   374→COPY go.mod go.sum ./\n   375→RUN go mod download\n   376→COPY . .\n   377→RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o /cloche-agent ./cmd/cloche-agent\n   378→\n   379→FROM ubuntu:24.04\n   380→RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y git <your-deps> && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n   381→RUN npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\n   382→COPY --from=builder /cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/cloche-agent\n   383→RUN useradd -m -s /bin/bash agent\n   384→WORKDIR /workspace\n   385→RUN chown agent:agent /workspace\n   386→USER agent\n   387→```\n   388→\n   389→Key requirements for the image:\n   390→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   391→- `git` installed (for pushing results back)\n   392→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps the command with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   393→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   394→- Your project's build dependencies\n   395→\n   396→The daemon automatically rebuilds the image when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes\n   397→(see `cloche run` above). To build manually:\n   398→```\n   399→docker build -t my-project-agent -f .cloche/Dockerfile .\n   400→CLOCHE_IMAGE=my-project-agent:latest bin/cloched\n   401→```\n   402→\n   403→### 6. Run it\n   404→\n   405→```\n   406→cd my-project\n   407→cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add feature X\"\n   408→```\n   409→\n   410→## Writing Workflows\n   411→\n   412→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in the `.cloche/` directory. See\n   413→[workflows.md](workflows.md) for full DSL reference.\n   414→\n   415→### Step Types\n   416→\n   417→**Agent steps** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent autonomously:\n   418→\n   419→```\n   420→step implement {\n   421→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n   422→  results = [success, fail]\n   423→}\n   424→```\n   425→\n   426→**Script steps** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command:\n   427→\n   428→```\n   429→step test {\n   430→  run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n   431→  results = [success, fail]\n   432→}\n   433→```\n   434→\n   435→### Wiring\n   436→\n   437→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   438→\n   439→```\n   440→implement:success -> test\n   441→implement:fail -> abort\n   442→test:success -> done\n   443→test:fail -> fix\n   444→```\n   445→\n   446→`done` and `abort` are built-in terminals for success and failure.\n   447→\n   448→### Retry Loops\n   449→\n   450→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   451→\n   452→```\n   453→test:fail -> fix\n   454→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   455→fix:fail -> abort\n   456→```\n   457→\n   458→### Max Attempts\n   459→\n   460→Limit retries on agent steps. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   461→\n   462→```\n   463→step fix {\n   464→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   465→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   466→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   467→}\n   468→```\n   469→\n   470→### Parallel Branches\n   471→\n   472→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   473→\n   474→```\n   475→test:success -> lint\n   476→test:success -> quality\n   477→```\n   478→\n   479→### Collect (Join)\n   480→\n   481→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   482→\n   483→```\n   484→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   485→```\n   486→\n   487→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   488→\n   489→### Agent Command Override\n   490→\n   491→Agent steps use Claude Code by default. Override per-step:\n   492→\n   493→```\n   494→step implement {\n   495→  prompt = \"...\"\n   496→  agent_command = \"aider\"\n   497→  results = [success, fail]\n   498→}\n   499→```\n   500→\n   501→Or at the workflow level via a `container` block:\n   502→\n   503→```\n   504→workflow \"develop\" {\n   505→  container {\n   506→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n   507→  }\n   508→  ...\n   509→}\n   510→```\n   511→\n   512→Or globally via `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable.\n   513→\n   514→Priority (highest to lowest): step-level `agent_command`, workflow-level\n   515→`container { agent_command }`, `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var, default (`claude`).\n   516→\n   517→### Agent Fallback Chains\n   518→\n   519→Use a comma-separated list in `agent_command` to configure fallback chains. If\n   520→the first agent errors without reporting a result, the system tries the next:\n   521→\n   522→```\n   523→step implement {\n   524→  prompt = \"...\"\n   525→  agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   526→  results = [success, fail]\n   527→}\n   528→```\n   529→\n   530→Fallback rules:\n   531→- **Command not found or failed to start** — fall back to next command\n   532→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — fall back to next command\n   533→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   534→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   535→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   536→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   537→\n   538→Known agents have default arguments (e.g., Claude gets\n   539→`-p --output-format text --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Other agents receive\n   540→the prompt on stdin with no extra flags. Override with `agent_args` at the step\n   541→or workflow level.\n   542→\n   543→## Result Protocol\n   544→\n   545→Steps report results by writing a marker to stdout:\n   546→\n   547→```\n   548→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   549→```\n   550→\n   551→For script steps, if no marker is written, the exit code determines the result:\n   552→0 = `success`, non-zero = `fail`. Agent steps follow the same convention.\n   553→\n   554→## Prompt Assembly\n   555→\n   556→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from multiple sources:\n   557→\n   558→1. The step's `prompt` content (inline or from `file()`)\n   559→2. The user prompt from `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt`)\n   560→3. Validation output from `.cloche/<run-id>/output/*.log` (output from previous script steps)\n   561→4. Result selection instructions listing the step's declared results\n   562→\n   563→## Project Directory Layout\n   564→\n   565→```\n   566→my-project/\n   567→├── .cloche/\n   568→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow definition\n   569→│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow (runs on host)\n   570→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image\n   571→│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration (orchestration, evolution)\n   572→│   ├── prompts/\n   573→│   │   ├── implement.md      # Prompt templates\n   574→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   575→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   576→│   ├── scripts/\n   577→│   │   └── prepare-prompt.sh # Host-side prompt generation script\n   578→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/ in container\n   579→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   580→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   581→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt (from --prompt flag)\n   582→│       ├── output/\n   583→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified chronological log (status + script + LLM)\n   584→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   585→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation output\n   586→│       ├── attempt_count/\n   587→│       │   └── fix           # Retry counter for max_attempts\n   588→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   589→├── src/                      # Existing project source (untouched)\n   590→├── CLAUDE.md                 # Host CLAUDE.md\n   591→└── .git/\n   592→```\n   593→\n   594→## Daemon Configuration\n   595→\n   596→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   597→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   598→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address (unix socket or TCP) |\n   599→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   600→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` (container) or `local` (subprocess, for dev) |\n   601→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   602→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | — | HTTP address for the web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   603→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | (auto-detected) | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   604→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | — | Command for LLM calls — evolution and merge conflict resolution (e.g. `claude`) |\n   605→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Passed into Docker containers |\n   606→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | — | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   607→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | — | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   608→\n   609→### Client Configuration\n   610→\n   611→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   612→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   613→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon address (gRPC) |\n   614→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address (web dashboard, `cloche logs --follow`) |\n   615→\n   616→## Build Commands\n   617→\n   618→```\n   619→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   620→make test           # Run all tests\n   621→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   622→make lint           # Run go vet\n   623→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   624→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   625→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   626→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   627→```\n   628→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"843502bc-3d5c-43fd-9244-ee919bbc5a7b","uuid":"ae1490c7-b931-4a0e-ba6f-ffae09f20a77","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"# Usage\n\nCloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You write a\nworkflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, point Cloche at a project directory, and it\nhandles execution, retry logic, and status tracking.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n- Go 1.25+\n- Docker\n- Git\n- An `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (for agent steps using Claude Code)\n\nFor detailed installation options (pre-built binaries, `go install`, Homebrew,\nDocker-based usage), see [INSTALL.md](INSTALL.md).\n\n## Quick Start\n\n### 1. Build everything\n\n```\nmake build\nmake docker-build\n```\n\nThis produces `bin/cloche`, `bin/cloched`, `bin/cloche-agent`, and the\n`cloche-agent:latest` Docker image.\n\n### 2. Start the daemon\n\n```\nbin/cloched\n```\n\nThe daemon listens on a Unix socket at `/tmp/cloche.sock` by default. It\nmanages Docker containers, tracks run state in SQLite, and handles\ncontainer cleanup. Containers are automatically removed after successful\nruns unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their\ncontainer for debugging.\n\nTo enable the web dashboard, set `CLOCHE_HTTP` (e.g.\n`CLOCHE_HTTP=:8080 bin/cloched`). The dashboard is not started unless\nthis variable is set.\n\n### 3. Run a workflow\n\nFrom your project directory (must be inside a git repository):\n\n```\ncd my-project\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add user authentication\"\n```\n\nThis will:\n1. Write your prompt to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`\n2. Create a Docker container and copy your entire project into it (no bind mounts)\n3. Apply any override files from `.cloche/overrides/` on top\n4. Start the container, which runs `cloche-agent` to walk the workflow graph\n5. When the workflow finishes, the daemon extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch\n\n### 4. Monitor progress\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\ncloche list\n```\n\n### 5. Get the results\n\nWhen the run completes, the agent's work is on a git branch:\n\n```\ngit branch | grep cloche/\ngit diff main..cloche/<run-id>\n```\n\nTo merge results into your working branch:\n\n```\ngit merge cloche/<run-id>\n# or cherry-pick, rebase, etc.\n```\n\nTo clean up run branches:\n\n```\ngit branch -D cloche/<run-id>\n```\n\n## Container Isolation Model\n\nCloche provides **total filesystem isolation** between the host and container:\n\n- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the entire project root into the container at\n  `/workspace/`. No bind mounts for project files. Override files from\n  `.cloche/overrides/` are then copied on top (e.g., a container-specific\n  `CLAUDE.md`). The `.git/` directory is included so agents have git context.\n- **Files out**: When the workflow completes, the daemon extracts results from\n  the container via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits them to a\n  `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n- **Auth mounts**: `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` are bind-mounted read-only\n  for Claude Code OAuth session reuse. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed as an\n  environment variable.\n- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n\nYour project directory is never modified by the container. All changes live\non the run branch until you explicitly merge them.\n\n## CLI Reference\n\n### `cloche init`\n\nScaffold a new Cloche project in the current directory.\n\n```\ncloche init [--workflow <name>] [--base-image <base>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--base-image <base>` | `cloche-base:latest` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n\nCreates `.cloche/` with a workflow file, Dockerfile, configuration file\n(`config.toml`), prompt templates (`implement.md`, `fix.md`,\n`update-docs.md`), a host orchestration workflow (`host.cloche`), a\nprompt generation script (`scripts/prepare-prompt.sh`), and a version\nmarker. Skips files that already exist.\nAlso adds gitignore entries for runtime state directories.\n\n### `cloche health`\n\nShow project health summary based on recent run results.\n\n```\ncloche health\n```\n\nRequires `CLOCHE_HTTP` to be set (e.g. `export CLOCHE_HTTP=localhost:8080`).\nFetches health data from the daemon's HTTP API (`GET /api/projects`) and\ndisplays a table with per-project pass/fail counts:\n\n```\nPROJECT          STATUS    PASSED  FAILED  TOTAL\nmy-project       green     5       0       5\nother-project    yellow    3       2       5\n```\n\nStatus is colored (green/yellow/red) when output is a TTY.\n\n### `cloche run`\n\nLaunch a workflow run.\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche` in the project directory. |\n| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` and injected into agent steps. |\n| `--keep-container` | Keep the Docker container even on success (default: remove on success). Failed runs always keep their container for debugging. |\n\nThe current working directory is used as the project directory. It must be\ninside a git repository (Cloche needs the repo root for result extraction\nvia git worktrees).\n\nWhen starting a run, the daemon checks whether the Docker image is up-to-date\nwith the project's `.cloche/Dockerfile`. If the Dockerfile has changed since\nthe last build (tracked via a SHA-256 label on the image), the daemon rebuilds\nthe image automatically before launching the container.\n\n### `cloche status`\n\nCheck the status of a run.\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\n```\n\nOutput includes the run state, active steps, and per-step results with timestamps.\n\n### `cloche list`\n\nList runs (last hour by default).\n\n```\ncloche list [--all]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--all` | Show all runs, not just the last hour. |\n\nColumns: run ID, workflow name, state, container ID (if running), error message (if failed).\n\n### `cloche logs`\n\nShow logs for a run.\n\n```\ncloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [--follow]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Show only logs of the specified type (`full` = unified log, `script` = script output, `llm` = LLM conversation). |\n| `--follow`, `-f` | Stream live log lines via SSE. Color-coded by type: status (blue), LLM (green), script (default). Exits when the run completes. Connects to the daemon's HTTP endpoint (see `CLOCHE_HTTP` in Client Configuration). |\n\nWithout flags, shows the unified log (`full.log`) if available, otherwise streams\nstep start/completion events and run results.\nWith `--follow`, connects to the SSE endpoint and prints log lines in real-time.\n\n### `cloche poll`\n\nWait for a run to finish, printing progress updates.\n\n```\ncloche poll <run-id>\n```\n\nPolls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure or if the container\ndies unexpectedly.\n\n### `cloche stop`\n\nCancel a running workflow.\n\n```\ncloche stop <run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche delete`\n\nDelete a retained Docker container. Accepts either a Docker container name/ID\nor a Cloche run ID. If given a run ID, the daemon looks up the associated\ncontainer.\n\n```\ncloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche orchestrate`\n\nDispatch ready workflow runs for the current project. Checks the project's\nissue tracker for unclaimed tasks, generates prompts, and launches runs.\n\n```\ncloche orchestrate\n```\n\nUses the current working directory as the project directory. Prints \"No ready\nwork found.\" if there are no tasks to dispatch, or \"Dispatched N run(s).\"\nwith the count.\n\n### `cloche shutdown`\n\nShut down the daemon.\n\n```\ncloche shutdown\n```\n\n## Setting Up a New Project\n\n### 1. Scaffold the project\n\nRun `cloche init` from your project root to create the `.cloche/` directory with\ndefault workflow, Dockerfile, and prompt templates:\n\n```\ncd my-project\ncloche init\n```\n\nOr create the structure manually:\n\n### 2. Create a workflow file\n\nAdd `.cloche/<name>.cloche`:\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  step update-docs {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/update-docs.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n\n  test:success -> update-docs\n  test:fail -> fix\n\n  fix:success -> test\n  fix:fail -> abort\n  fix:give-up -> abort\n\n  update-docs:success -> done\n  update-docs:fail -> done\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Write prompt templates\n\nCreate `.cloche/prompts/` with markdown files:\n\n**`.cloche/prompts/implement.md`** — Instructions for the initial implementation:\n```markdown\nYou are working on a project. Implement the following change:\n\n## User Request\n(The user prompt is injected automatically by the agent adapter)\n\n## Guidelines\n- Follow existing project conventions\n- Write tests for new functionality\n- Run tests locally before declaring success\n```\n\n**`.cloche/prompts/fix.md`** — Instructions for fixing failures:\n```markdown\nThe previous attempt had failures. Review the output logs in .cloche/output/\nand fix the issues.\n\n## Guidelines\n- Read the test/lint output carefully\n- Fix the root cause, not the symptoms\n- Run tests again to verify your fix\n```\n\n**`.cloche/prompts/update-docs.md`** — Instructions for keeping docs in sync:\n```markdown\nReview the CLI source code and update usage documentation to reflect any changes.\n```\n\n### 4. Add overrides (optional)\n\nFiles in `.cloche/overrides/` are copied on top of `/workspace/` in the\ncontainer. Use this for container-specific configuration:\n\n```\n.cloche/overrides/\n  CLAUDE.md              # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (replaces host version)\n```\n\n### 5. Make sure your project builds in the container\n\nThe default Dockerfile generated by `cloche init` uses `cloche-base:latest` as its\nbase image (configurable via `--base-image`). If your project needs different\ndependencies, edit `.cloche/Dockerfile`:\n\n```dockerfile\nFROM golang:1.25 AS builder\nWORKDIR /src\nCOPY go.mod go.sum ./\nRUN go mod download\nCOPY . .\nRUN CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o /cloche-agent ./cmd/cloche-agent\n\nFROM ubuntu:24.04\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y git <your-deps> && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\nRUN npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\nCOPY --from=builder /cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/cloche-agent\nRUN useradd -m -s /bin/bash agent\nWORKDIR /workspace\nRUN chown agent:agent /workspace\nUSER agent\n```\n\nKey requirements for the image:\n- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n- `git` installed (for pushing results back)\n- An `agent` user (cloche wraps the command with `chown` + `su agent`)\n- `/workspace` as the working directory\n- Your project's build dependencies\n\nThe daemon automatically rebuilds the image when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes\n(see `cloche run` above). To build manually:\n```\ndocker build -t my-project-agent -f .cloche/Dockerfile .\nCLOCHE_IMAGE=my-project-agent:latest bin/cloched\n```\n\n### 6. Run it\n\n```\ncd my-project\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add feature X\"\n```\n\n## Writing Workflows\n\nWorkflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in the `.cloche/` directory. See\n[workflows.md](workflows.md) for full DSL reference.\n\n### Step Types\n\n**Agent steps** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent autonomously:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n**Script steps** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command:\n\n```\nstep test {\n  run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n### Wiring\n\nConnect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n\n```\nimplement:success -> test\nimplement:fail -> abort\ntest:success -> done\ntest:fail -> fix\n```\n\n`done` and `abort` are built-in terminals for success and failure.\n\n### Retry Loops\n\nWire failures back to earlier steps:\n\n```\ntest:fail -> fix\nfix:success -> test    // retry the test\nfix:fail -> abort\n```\n\n### Max Attempts\n\nLimit retries on agent steps. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n\n```\nstep fix {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n  max_attempts = \"2\"\n  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Parallel Branches\n\nWire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n\n```\ntest:success -> lint\ntest:success -> quality\n```\n\n### Collect (Join)\n\nSynchronize parallel branches:\n\n```\ncollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n```\n\n`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n\n### Agent Command Override\n\nAgent steps use Claude Code by default. Override per-step:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = \"...\"\n  agent_command = \"aider\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\nOr at the workflow level via a `container` block:\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nOr globally via `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable.\n\nPriority (highest to lowest): step-level `agent_command`, workflow-level\n`container { agent_command }`, `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var, default (`claude`).\n\n### Agent Fallback Chains\n\nUse a comma-separated list in `agent_command` to configure fallback chains. If\nthe first agent errors without reporting a result, the system tries the next:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = \"...\"\n  agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\nFallback rules:\n- **Command not found or failed to start** — fall back to next command\n- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — fall back to next command\n- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n\nKnown agents have default arguments (e.g., Claude gets\n`-p --output-format text --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Other agents receive\nthe prompt on stdin with no extra flags. Override with `agent_args` at the step\nor workflow level.\n\n## Result Protocol\n\nSteps report results by writing a marker to stdout:\n\n```\nCLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n```\n\nFor script steps, if no marker is written, the exit code determines the result:\n0 = `success`, non-zero = `fail`. Agent steps follow the same convention.\n\n## Prompt Assembly\n\nWhen an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from multiple sources:\n\n1. The step's `prompt` content (inline or from `file()`)\n2. The user prompt from `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt`)\n3. Validation output from `.cloche/<run-id>/output/*.log` (output from previous script steps)\n4. Result selection instructions listing the step's declared results\n\n## Project Directory Layout\n\n```\nmy-project/\n├── .cloche/\n│   ├── develop.cloche        # Container workflow definition\n│   ├── host.cloche           # Host orchestration workflow (runs on host)\n│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image\n│   ├── config.toml           # Project configuration (orchestration, evolution)\n│   ├── prompts/\n│   │   ├── implement.md      # Prompt templates\n│   │   ├── fix.md\n│   │   └── update-docs.md\n│   ├── scripts/\n│   │   └── prepare-prompt.sh # Host-side prompt generation script\n│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/ in container\n│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt (from --prompt flag)\n│       ├── output/\n│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified chronological log (status + script + LLM)\n│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation output\n│       ├── attempt_count/\n│       │   └── fix           # Retry counter for max_attempts\n│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n├── src/                      # Existing project source (untouched)\n├── CLAUDE.md                 # Host CLAUDE.md\n└── .git/\n```\n\n## Daemon Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address (unix socket or TCP) |\n| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` (container) or `local` (subprocess, for dev) |\n| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | — | HTTP address for the web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | (auto-detected) | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | — | Command for LLM calls — evolution and merge conflict resolution (e.g. `claude`) |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Passed into Docker containers |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | — | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | — | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n\n### Client Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon address (gRPC) |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address (web dashboard, `cloche logs --follow`) |\n\n## Build Commands\n\n```\nmake build          # Build all binaries to bin/\nmake test           # Run all tests\nmake test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\nmake lint           # Run go vet\nmake proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\nmake docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\nmake install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\nmake clean          # Remove bin/\n```\n","numLines":628,"startLine":1,"totalLines":628}}}
